b'' b'' b' si neatly separates the concepts of "mass", "force" and "weight"' b' which have gotten horribly tangled up in the us system.' b'' b' this is not a problem with english units. a pound is defined to' b' be a unit of force, period. there is a perfectly good unit called' b' the slug, which is the mass of an object weighing lbs at sea level.' b' (g ft/sec^2, of course.)' b'' b'' b'american military english units, perhaps. us real english types were once' b'taught that a pound is mass and a poundal is force (being that force that' b'causes pound to accelerate at ft.s-2). we had a rare olde tyme doing' b'our exams in those units and metric as well.' b'' b'american, perhaps, but nothing military about it. i learned (mostly)' b'slugs when we talked english units in high school physics and while' b"the teacher was an ex-navy fighter jock the book certainly wasn't" b'produced by the military.' b'' b'[poundals were just too flinking small and made the math come out' b'funny; sort of the same reason proponents of si give for using that.]' b'' b'--' b'"insisting on perfect safety is for people who don\'t have the balls to live' b'in the real world." mary shafer, nasa ames dryden' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' 